es that the debates around these issues, as well as the consumer culture associated with them, helped give the British world a sense of cohesion and identity. This book will be essential reading for historians of imperialism and globalisation, and includes contributions from some of the most prominent historians of British imperial and cultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulturexHistory. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnti-slavery.  aBritish Empire.  aBritish World.  aCultural History.  aHumanitarianism.  aIndia.  aInformal Empire.1 aBayly, C. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrosbie, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrosbie, Barry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEverill, Bronwen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampton, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampton, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarling, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilliard, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Philippa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNechtman, Tillman W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTusan, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiener, Martin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://